Awesome NextjsAwesome
A carefully selected list of the best resources available in the Next.js community.

Nextjs is an open-source framework for building high-quality small and large-scale web applications using Reactjs with modern tools and technology.

To stay updated, follow the GitHub Repository and give our repository a star. This will help others discover it, encourage more developers to contribute, and build a solid list. Also, we encourage you to share our repository on your social media platforms, like X (previously known as Twitter).

You can also check out awesome documentation if you are looking for a list of documentation tools.

Read our guidelines before sharing your favourite library, tool, or template on the awesome nextjs repository.

# 🎮 FFLU | Final Fantasy Level-Up! ![FFLU Logo](https://media.forgecdn.net/attachments/1260/965/638506516785357823-1-png.png) ## 🎮 RGX Mods - RealmGX Community Project ### 🎵 _Experience the legendary Final Fantasy level-up sound!_ 🎵 **FFLU | Final Fantasy Level-Up!** is a professional World of Warcraft addon that brings the iconic Final Fantasy level-up sound to your WoW experience. As part of the **RGX Mods** collection, it delivers premium quality with extensive customization options, multi-language support, and seamless integration across all WoW versions. *** ## 🌟 Join the RGX Mods Community! **💬 RealmGX Discord - Your Gaming Home!** [![Join Discord](https://img.shields.io/badge/Join Our Discord-RealmGX Community-7289da?style=for-the-badge&logo=discord&logoColor=white&labelColor=5865F2)](https://discord.gg/N7kdKAHVVF) **🎮 Realm Gamers eXtreme - Where WoW Enthusiasts Unite!** **✨ What awaits you in our Discord:** * 🛠️ Instant addon support from the RGX Mods team * 🎯 Feature requests and direct dev communication * 🚀 Beta testing opportunities for new releases * 🤝 Community of **WoW players** sharing tips and experiences * 📢 First to know about new RGX Mods releases * 🎉 Events, giveaways, and community activities *** ## 🎯 What is FFLU? **FFLU | Final Fantasy Level-Up!** is a professional World of Warcraft addon that brings the iconic Final Fantasy level-up sound to your WoW experience. As part of the **RGX Mods** collection, it delivers premium quality with extensive customization options, multi-language support, and seamless integration across all WoW versions. This addon replaces the default WoW level-up sound with the classic **"LEVEL UP!"** chime from the Final Fantasy series, bringing nostalgic gaming memories to your World of Warcraft leveling experience. *** ## ✨ Features 🎵 Iconic Sound - Authentic Final Fantasy level-up chime on every level gain 🎚️ Multiple Variants - Choose from high, medium, or low quality sound versions 🔇 Smart Management - Automatically mutes default WoW level-up sound ⚙️ Complete Control - Enable/disable features with comprehensive slash commands 💾 Persistent Settings - Your preferences are saved between sessions 🌍 Multi-Language - English, German, French, Spanish, and Russian localization 🎨 Professional UI - Clean interface with consistent RGX Mods branding 🛡️ Error-Free - Comprehensive error handling and validation 🔧 Reset Function - Easily reset all settings to defaults *** ## 🚀 Quick Start 1. **Install** FFLU from your preferred platform 2. **Launch** World of Warcraft 3. **Level up** and enjoy the iconic sound! 4. **Customize** with `/fflu help` to see all options *** ## 📋 Command Reference
/fflu help # Show all available commands
/fflu enable # Enable the addon
/fflu disable # Disable the addon
/fflu toggle # Toggle addon on/off
/fflu test # Play a test sound
/fflu status # Show current settings
/fflu sound high/medium/low # Set sound quality
/fflu volume Master/SFX/Music/Ambience # Set volume channel
/fflu reset # Reset all settings to defaults
### Usage Examples
/fflu sound high # Use high quality sound
/fflu volume SFX # Play on SFX channel
/fflu disable # Temporarily disable
/fflu test # Test current sound
/fflu status # Check settings
/fflu reset # Reset to defaults
*** ## 🎮 Advanced Configuration ### Sound Variants * **High:** Premium quality for audiophiles * **Medium:** Balanced quality and performance (default) * **Low:** Lightweight for performance-focused setups ### Persistent Settings All your preferences are automatically saved: * Addon enable/disable state * Selected sound variant * Volume channel preference * Default sound muting preference * Welcome message display ### Multi-Language Support FFLU automatically detects your WoW client language: * **English** (Default) * **Deutsch** (German) * **Français** (French) * **Español** (Spanish) * **Русский** (Russian) - _New!_ by ZamestoTV *** ## 🎮 Compatibility The War Within - Interface 110105 | ✅ Fully Supported | FFLU.toc Mists of Pandaria Classic - Interface 50500 | ✅ Fully Supported | FFLU_Mists.toc Cataclysm Classic - Interface 40402 | ✅ Fully Supported | FFLU_Cata.toc Wrath of the Lich King Classic - Interface 30403 | ✅ Fully Supported | FFLU_Wrath.toc Burning Crusade Classic - Interface 20504 | ✅ Fully Supported | FFLU_BCC.toc Classic Era / Hardcore / SoD - Interface 11507 | ✅ Fully Supported | FFLU_Vanilla.toc **Note:** Classic Era, Hardcore, and Season of Discovery all use the same interface version and TOC file. *** ## 📥 Installation 1. **Download** from your preferred platform: * [CurseForge](https://www.curseforge.com/wow/addons/fflu) * [Wago.io](https://addons.wago.io/addons/fflu) * [WoWInterface](https://www.wowinterface.com/downloads/info26252) * [GitHub](https://github.com/donniedice/FFLU) 2. **Extract** to your WoW AddOns directory: * **Retail:** World of Warcraft/retail/Interface/AddOns * **Classic:** World of Warcraft/classic/Interface/AddOns * **Classic Era:** World of Warcraft/classic_era/Interface/AddOns 3. **Restart** WoW and enable in AddOns menu *** ## 🆕 What's New ### v2.1.14 - GitHub Stats Card Copy and paste this into your markdown, and that's it. Simple! Change the ?username= value to your GitHub username. [![Anurag's GitHub stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra)](https://github.com/anuraghazra/github-readme-stats) Warning By default, the stats card only shows statistics like stars, commits, and pull requests from public repositories. To show private statistics on the stats card, you should deploy your own instance using your own GitHub API token. Note Available ranks are S (top 1%), A+ (12.5%), A (25%), A- (37.5%), B+ (50%), B (62.5%), B- (75%), C+ (87.5%) and C (everyone). This ranking scheme is based on the Japanese academic grading system. The global percentile is calculated as a weighted sum of percentiles for each statistic (number of commits, pull requests, reviews, issues, stars, and followers), based on the cumulative distribution function of the exponential and the log-normal distributions. The implementation can be investigated at src/calculateRank.js. The circle around the rank shows 100 minus the global percentile. Hiding individual stats You can pass a query parameter &hide= to hide any specific stats with comma-separated values. Options: &hide=stars,commits,prs,issues,contribs ![Anurag's GitHub stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&hide=contribs,prs) Showing additional individual stats You can pass a query parameter &show= to show any specific additional stats with comma-separated values. Options: &show=reviews,discussions_started,discussions_answered,prs_merged,prs_merged_percentage ![Anurag's GitHub stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&show=reviews,discussions_started,discussions_answered,prs_merged,prs_merged_percentage) Showing icons To enable icons, you can pass &show_icons=true in the query param, like so: ![Anurag's GitHub stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&show_icons=true) Themes With inbuilt themes, you can customize the look of the card without doing any manual customization. Use &theme=THEME_NAME parameter like so : ![Anurag's GitHub stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&show_icons=true&theme=radical) All inbuilt themes GitHub Readme Stats comes with several built-in themes (e.g. dark, radical, merko, gruvbox, tokyonight, onedark, cobalt, synthwave, highcontrast, dracula). GitHub Readme Stats Themes You can look at a preview for all available themes or checkout the theme config file. Please note that we paused the addition of new themes to decrease maintenance efforts; all pull requests related to new themes will be closed. Responsive Card Theme Anurag's GitHub stats-Dark Since GitHub will re-upload the cards and serve them from their CDN, we can not infer the browser/GitHub theme on the server side. There are, however, four methods you can use to create dynamics themes on the client side. Use the transparent theme We have included a transparent theme that has a transparent background. This theme is optimized to look good on GitHub's dark and light default themes. You can enable this theme using the &theme=transparent parameter like so: ![Anurag's GitHub stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&show_icons=true&theme=transparent) 👀 Show example Add transparent alpha channel to a themes bg_color You can use the bg_color parameter to make any of the available themes transparent. This is done by setting the bg_color to a color with a transparent alpha channel (i.e. bg_color=00000000): ![Anurag's GitHub stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&show_icons=true&bg_color=00000000) 👀 Show example Use GitHub's theme context tag You can use GitHub's theme context tags to switch the theme based on the user GitHub theme automatically. This is done by appending #gh-dark-mode-only or #gh-light-mode-only to the end of an image URL. This tag will define whether the image specified in the markdown is only shown to viewers using a light or a dark GitHub theme: [![Anurag's GitHub stats-Dark](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&show_icons=true&theme=dark#gh-dark-mode-only)](https://github.com/anuraghazra/github-readme-stats#gh-dark-mode-only) [![Anurag's GitHub stats-Light](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api?username=anuraghazra&show_icons=true&theme=default#gh-light-mode-only)](https://github.com/anuraghazra/github-readme-stats#gh-light-mode-only) 👀 Show example Use GitHub's new media feature You can use GitHub's new media feature in HTML to specify whether to display images for light or dark themes. This is done using the HTML element in combination with the prefers-color-scheme media feature. 👀 Show example Customization You can customize the appearance of all your cards however you wish with URL parameters. Warning By default, the language card shows language results only from public repositories. To include languages used in private repositories, you should deploy your own instance using your own GitHub API token. Note Top Languages does not indicate the user's skill level or anything like that; it's a GitHub metric to determine which languages have the most code on GitHub. It is a new feature of github-readme-stats. Warning This card shows language usage only inside your own non-forked repositories, not depending on who the author of the commits is. It does not include your contributions into another users/organizations repositories. Currently there are no way to get this data from GitHub API. If you want this behavior to be improved you can support this feature request created by @rickstaa inside GitHub Community. Warning Currently this card shows data only about first 100 repositories. This is because GitHub API limitations which cause downtimes of public instances (see #1471). In future this behavior will be improved by releasing GitHub action or providing environment variables for user's own instances. Usage Copy-paste this code into your readme and change the links. Endpoint: api/top-langs?username=anuraghazra [![Top Langs](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api/top-langs/?username=anuraghazra)](https://github.com/anuraghazra/github-readme-stats) Language stats algorithm We use the following algorithm to calculate the languages percentages on the language card: ranking_index = (byte_count ^ size_weight) * (repo_count ^ count_weight) By default, only the byte count is used for determining the languages percentages shown on the language card (i.e. size_weight=1 and count_weight=0). You can, however, use the &size_weight= and &count_weight= options to weight the language usage calculation. The values must be positive real numbers. More details about the algorithm can be found here. &size_weight=1&count_weight=0 - (default) Orders by byte count. &size_weight=0.5&count_weight=0.5 - (recommended) Uses both byte and repo count for ranking &size_weight=0&count_weight=1 - Orders by repo count ![Top Langs](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api/top-langs/?username=anuraghazra&size_weight=0.5&count_weight=0.5) Exclude individual repositories You can use the &exclude_repo=repo1,repo2 parameter to exclude individual repositories. ![Top Langs](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api/top-langs/?username=anuraghazra&exclude_repo=github-readme-stats,anuraghazra.github.io) Hide individual languages You can use &hide=language1,language2 parameter to hide individual languages. ![Top Langs](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api/top-langs/?username=anuraghazra&hide=javascript,html) Show more languages You can use the &langs_count= option to increase or decrease the number of languages shown on the card. Got it — you want to **orchestrate Claude Code** so that it uses **your other connected LLM agents** (DeepSeek GPT, Gemini) to cross-check and flesh out BLU’s **scope and functionality** with actual repository code access.

Here’s a practical approach that works well when one model (Claude Code) has repo access but you want multiple models to collaborate:

---

## **1. Frame the Objective Clearly**

Claude Code needs an explicit job:

* **Primary**: Extract all relevant implementation details from BLU\_Classic’s code (functions, event flow, UI, saved vars, sound logic).
* **Secondary**: Collaborate with other agents (DeepSeek GPT, Gemini) to verify interpretation, document scope, and identify edge cases.

You tell Claude Code something like:

> *"Your goal is to produce an authoritative technical write-up of the **scope and functionality** of the BLU\_Classic addon.
> Step 1: Use your repo access to extract all Lua files, `.toc` files, and related resources, and produce a structured outline of all components (per file).
> Step 2: Send that outline to DeepSeek GPT to verify completeness and suggest missing pieces.
> Step 3: Send the refined outline and any identified gaps to Gemini to produce a final, reader-friendly scope and functionality summary.
> Step 4: Return the combined, reconciled result, noting where models disagreed."*

---

## **2. Break the Job Into Stages for the Agents**

### **Stage 1 — Claude Code** (repo-connected model)

* Traverse repo file tree.
* For each `.lua` and `.toc`:

  * Extract purpose, events handled, major functions, cross-file dependencies.
  * Record all configuration tables (options, defaults).
  * Map event → handler → sound.
  * Identify UI components and slash commands.
* Output as **JSON/structured table** for hand-off.

### **Stage 2 — DeepSeek GPT** (pattern-recognition + code reasoning)

* Input: JSON/structured table from Stage 1.
* Tasks:

  * Detect missing files, unused functions, event coverage gaps.
  * Cross-check function naming vs. actual event binding.
  * Flag edge cases (e.g., overwritten event handlers, localization issues).
  * Suggest extra scope items Claude might have missed.

### **Stage 3 — Gemini** (natural-language synthesis)

* Input: Claude’s structured table + DeepSeek’s gap analysis.
* Tasks:

  * Merge into **one unified, narrative write-up**.
  * Include:

    * High-level scope statement.
    * Functional breakdown (events, menus, sounds, saved vars).
    * Technical implementation overview.
    * Version-specific behavior.
  * Present in human-readable sections for documentation or README.

---

## **3. Prompt Templates for Each Agent**

### **Claude Code Prompt**

```plaintext
You have repo access.  
Goal: Extract a complete technical map of BLU_Classic's scope and functionality.

1. Get the full folder tree.
2. For each Lua file:
   - File name
   - Purpose in addon
   - Public functions & what they do
   - Events registered & handlers
   - Cross-file dependencies
   - Any user-facing commands/UI
3. From .toc files:
   - Interface version targets
   - File load order
   - SavedVariables listed
4. Produce output as structured JSON like:
{
 "files": [
   {
     "name": "core.lua",
     "purpose": "...",
     "events": [...],
     "functions": [{name: "...", desc: "..."}],
     "ui": [...],
     "depends_on": [...]
   }
 ],
 "saved_variables": [...],
 "versions_supported": [...]
}
Do NOT summarize — capture every detail for hand-off.
```

---

### **DeepSeek GPT Prompt**

```plaintext
You are reviewing Claude's technical map of BLU_Classic.

1. Cross-check that all events and functions in code are accounted for.
2. Identify missing:
   - Files not analyzed
   - Functions not documented
   - Event handlers overwritten or unused
   - UI/menu sections
3. Point out ambiguous areas that require inspection.
4. Suggest clarifying questions for the developer.
Output as a bullet list of:
- Gaps
- Risks
- Suggested clarifications
```

---

### **Gemini Prompt**

```plaintext
Using Claude's detailed technical map and DeepSeek's gap analysis, write a final
authoritative narrative describing BLU_Classic's:

1. Scope — what the addon is for, supported WoW events, intended player use cases.
2. Functionality — how it hooks into WoW APIs, event flow, menu/UI features, version-specific logic.
3. Technical implementation — per major file/module, summarize responsibilities.
4. Differences in Retail vs. Classic behavior.
5. Known limitations or risks.

Write it in clear, technical prose suitable for a developer audience.
```

---

## **4. Tips to Get Good Output**

* **Force sequential execution** — have Claude explicitly call the other agents in order, and only move to the next stage after merging feedback.
* **Ask for structured outputs** from Claude and DeepSeek to make Gemini’s merge job easier.
* **Preserve raw code references** in Claude’s output so Gemini can pull exact examples.

---

If you want, I can draft a **ready-to-run multi-agent orchestration script** that tells Claude exactly how to query your repo and chain results through DeepSeek and Gemini. That would make them work like one “super-reviewer” for BLU.

Do you want me to write that orchestration prompt/script next?

1.content:
Thanks — now that you’ve uploaded code I can give a real, concrete analysis of **scope** and **functionality** (what the addon actually does), plus call out bugs, missing pieces, and recommended fixes. I’ll cover:

* What the code *does* and the addon *scope* (based on the three uploaded files).
* How the addon implements that functionality (event flow, sound playback hooks, options integration).
* Concrete issues / bugs (with short explanations).
* Safe, focused code fixes (small diffs / replacement snippets you can apply).
* Next steps and what I still need to finish a full audit.

---

# 1) What this code actually implements — Scope & functionality (based on uploaded files)

**Primary scope**

* BLU is a lightweight event → sound mapper for milestone events (level up, quest accept/complete, achievements, reputation rank-ups, and several Retail-only events).
* It is **version aware** (vanilla / cata / retail) and enables/disables UI groups and event handlers depending on detected game version.
* It exposes an options UI via **AceConfig / AceConfigDialog** and supports **profiles** via AceDB / AceDBOptions.
* It mutes specific Blizzard sound IDs on startup for the current version (via a `muteSoundIDs` table).
* It provides debug printing and a welcome message toggle.

**Events handled** (from `initialization.lua` + functions in `core.lua`):

* PLAYER\_ENTERING\_WORLD (handler not in provided files)
* PLAYER\_LEVEL\_UP → `HandlePlayerLevelUp`
* QUEST\_ACCEPTED → `HandleQuestAccepted`
* QUEST\_TURNED\_IN → `HandleQuestTurnedIn`
* CHAT\_MSG\_SYSTEM → routed to reputation/delve logic (see quirks below)
* Retail-only (only registered when `GetGameVersion()` returns `"retail"`):
  `MAJOR_FACTION_RENOWN_LEVEL_CHANGED`, `PERKS_ACTIVITY_COMPLETED`, `ACHIEVEMENT_EARNED`, `HONOR_LEVEL_UPDATE`, `TRAIT_CONFIG_UPDATED`, `UPDATE_FACTION`, `UNIT_SPELLCAST_SUCCEEDED`, `PET_BATTLE_LEVEL_CHANGED`, `UNIT_PET_EXPERIENCE`, `PET_JOURNAL_LIST_UPDATE`

**UI / Options behavior**

* Options are constructed in `self.options` (not included in these uploads). `InitializeOptions()`:

  * Determines game version and removes incompatible option groups (so the options panel is tailored by version).
  * Sorts option groups and colorizes group/arg labels (via `AssignGroupColors`).
  * Registers the options table with AceConfig and adds it to Blizzard’s Interface Options.
  * Registers AceDB Profiles under the same UI.

**Sound playback**

* The files call `self:HandleEvent(...)` and `self:TestSound(...)` to perform play logic. These functions are not in the uploaded set, so I assume those live in another file (utils.lua / play.lua). The core file simply maps events to sound-selection keys and default sounds.

**Reputation handling**

* Reputation rank increases are detected by filtering `CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM` text (English message matching), then calling `ReputationRankIncrease()` which delegates to `HandleEvent("REPUTATION_RANK_INCREASE", ...)`.

**Delve companion (Retail)**

* Detects a chat system message like `"Brann Bronzebeard has reached Level X"` and triggers a DELVE\_LEVEL\_UP sound via `HandleEvent`.

---

# 2) How the implementation flows (high-level execution path)

1. **OnInitialize**

   * Create `self.db` via AceDB using `self.defaults`.
   * Populate missing `self.db.profile` keys with `self.defaults.profile` values.
   * Set `self.debugMode` and `self.showWelcomeMessage` from DB.
   * Register `/blu` chat command and events via `RegisterSharedEvents`.
   * Call `InitializeOptions()` — register AceConfig tables and add to Blizzard options (if `self.options` exists).
   * Mute sound IDs (from `muteSoundIDs[self:GetGameVersion()]`) using `MuteSoundFile`.
   * Print welcome message if enabled.

2. **Event Registration**

   * `RegisterSharedEvents()` builds an `events` table keyed by WoW event name and valued with the *method name string* to call.
   * It conditionally appends retail/cata-specific events.
   * For each `event, handler in pairs(events)` it registers the event with AceEvent if `self[handler]` is a function.

3. **Event Handlers in `core.lua`**

   * Each handler simply calls `self:HandleEvent(eventName, soundSelectKey, volumeKey, defaultSound, debugMessageKey)`.
   * Test functions call `self:TestSound(soundSelectKey, volumeKey, defaultSound, debugMessageKey)`.

4. **Chat message hooks**

   * `ReputationChatFrameHook()` installs a message filter for `CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM` via `ChatFrame_AddMessageEventFilter` — examines chat messages for English phrases like `"You are now Exalted with"` etc. and calls `ReputationRankIncrease(...)`.
   * `OnDelveCompanionLevelUp` listens for the same `CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM` and parses Brann messages.

---

# 3) Concrete issues and bugs (priority ordered)

### A — **CHAT\_MSG\_SYSTEM registration conflict / handler overwrite**

* In `RegisterSharedEvents()` you initially set `events.CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM = "ReputationChatFrameHook"`. Later, when `version == "retail"`, you set `events.CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM = "OnDelveCompanionLevelUp"`. Setting the same key overwrites the first value, so only one of the two methods will be registered for `CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM` (whichever assignment happens last).
* **Effect:** In retail, `ReputationChatFrameHook` will *not* be registered because it gets replaced. That will break reputation detection in retail builds.

### B — **ReputationChatFrameHook has many duplicated `elseif` branches with identical patterns**

* There are multiple `elseif string.match(msg, "Your standing with") then` checks repeated — they’re identical, so only the first will ever be reached. Those repeated blocks appear to be intended to match different rank strings but currently do not.
* Also `Mastermind` branch sets `"Hated"` when calling `ReputationRankIncrease` — likely a copy/paste mistake.
* **Effect:** Reputation rank detection will only work for the explicitly spelled-out strings (Exalted, Revered, etc.). The repeated `"Your standing with"` blocks do nothing useful and are confusing.

### C — **Localization dependence / hardcoded English strings**

* `ReputationChatFrameHook` uses English message fragments (`"You are now Exalted with"`, `"Your standing with"`, etc.). This will **fail on non-English clients**.
* **Effect:** Non-English locales will not trigger reputation sounds.

### D — **`ReputationRankIncrease` ignores faction name, uses only HandleEvent**

* It extracts `factionName` but never uses it. Possibly acceptable if you only need to trigger a generic reputation sound, but if the intention was to show which faction or do per-faction custom behavior, the function is incomplete.
* **Effect:** Potential missed opportunity for richer behavior; minor bug only if faction info expected.

### E — **`defaultSounds`, `self.defaults`, `self.options`, `muteSoundIDs`, and play functions missing from uploads**

* Many referenced resources and functions (HandleEvent, TestSound, defaults) are not in these three files. I need the rest of the code to confirm behavior and identify more issues.
* **Effect:** I cannot confirm exact playback mechanics, volume math, saved-variable schema, or options layout without those files.

### F — **`GetGameVersion()` logic could misclassify some clients**

* Uses `local _, _, _, interfaceVersion = GetBuildInfo()` and then numeric checks: `<20000` => vanilla, `>=40000 and <50000` => cata, `>=100000` => retail. That may be fine for targeted versions but consider edge cases for other BC/Wrath-era or future clients. Also `GetBuildInfo()` returns strings for some values in various clients (ensure `interfaceVersion` is numeric).
* **Effect:** Mis-detection could cause wrong event registration or option removal.

---

# 4) Suggested fixes (small patches / replacement snippets)

Below are focused changes you can apply to the uploaded files to fix the immediate bugs described. These patches assume minimal changes to other code.

### Fix 1 — Register both chat handlers (avoid overwrite)

Replace the `CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM` assignment logic in `RegisterSharedEvents()` with code that registers both handlers by registering the event once and ensuring both methods are called, or by adding a wrapper handler.

**Option A — preferred: register both by adding a wrapper dispatcher**

Replace the `events` building and registration lines that set `CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM` with this patch in `initialization.lua`:

```lua
-- remove earlier direct assignment of CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM in events table
-- after building events, handle CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM specially to call multiple handlers

local chatSystemHandlers = {}

-- add reputation handler for all versions
table.insert(chatSystemHandlers, "ReputationChatFrameHook")

if version == "retail" then
    -- retail also wants delve handler
    table.insert(chatSystemHandlers, "OnDelveCompanionLevelUp")
end

-- Register other events normally
for event, handler in pairs(events) do
    if event ~= "CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM" then
        if type(self[handler]) == "function" then
            self:RegisterEvent(event, handler)
        end
    end
end

-- Register CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM once with a dispatcher that calls all handlers we want
if #chatSystemHandlers > 0 then
    self:RegisterEvent("CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM", function(frame, event, ...)
        for _, handlerName in ipairs(chatSystemHandlers) do
            if type(self[handlerName]) == "function" then
                -- call handler method with same signature as normally used
                self[handlerName](self, event, ...)
            end
        end
    end)
end
```

**Why:** This ensures both reputation parsing and delve parsing receive `CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM` events regardless of version ordering. It avoids collision and is explicit.

---

### Fix 2 — Clean up `ReputationChatFrameHook()` and use a table-driven matcher

Replace the long repeated `elseif` chain with a table of patterns → rank mapping, making it maintainable, fix copy/paste mistakes, and make it easier to add localization later.

Replace the body of `ReputationChatFrameHook()` with:

```lua
function BLU:ReputationChatFrameHook()
    if BLU.chatFrameHooked then return end

    local rankPatterns = {
        ["You are now Exalted with"] = "Exalted",
        ["You are now Revered with"] = "Revered",
        ["You are now Honored with"] = "Honored",
        ["You are now Friendly with"] = "Friendly",
        ["You are now Neutral with"] = "Neutral",
        ["You are now Unfriendly with"] = "Unfriendly",
        ["You are now Hostile with"] = "Hostile",
        ["You are now Hated with"] = "Hated",
        -- legacy/alternate formats; if you need to match other English variants add here
        -- ["Your standing with .* has changed"] = "SomeRank",    -- example
    }

    ChatFrame_AddMessageEventFilter("CHAT_MSG_SYSTEM", function(_, _, msg)
        self:PrintDebugMessage("INCOMING_CHAT_MESSAGE: " .. tostring(msg))

        local rankFound = false
        for pattern, rankName in pairs(rankPatterns) do
            if string.find(msg, pattern, 1, true) then
                self:PrintDebugMessage("|cff00ff00Rank found: " .. rankName .. "|r")
                self:ReputationRankIncrease(rankName, msg)
                rankFound = true
                break
            end
        end

        if not rankFound then
            self:PrintDebugMessage("NO_RANK_FOUND")
        end

        return false
    end)

    BLU.chatFrameHooked = true
end
```

**Why:** Table-driven checks are easier to maintain and avoid accidental duplicate checks. `string.find(..., 1, true)` uses plain-text search (not pattern matching) to avoid pitfalls with magic characters; change if you need pattern matching.

---

### Fix 3 — Use locale-safe reputation detection (longer term)

Right now, detection is English-only. To make it locale-aware, you should **use WoW API where possible** (there are APIs for faction standing changes in Retail/Classic) or provide translations via localization tables. Example suggestion:

* Where API exists (Retail), prefer event-based faction APIs like `UPDATE_FACTION` and `C_Reputation.GetFactionParentalInfo()` etc. (requires further code and file additions).

You have:

```lua
self:HandleEvent("REPUTATION_RANK_INCREASE", "RepSoundSelect", "RepVolume", defaultSounds[6], "REPUTATION_RANK_INCREASE_TRIGGERED")
```

```lua
if factionName then
    factionName = factionName:gsub("%.$", ""):trim() -- remove trailing dot, whitespace (add trim helper)
```

## `core/WUICore.lua`

(Full file — minimal virtual tree, `useState`, `render`, naive reconciliation)

```lua
-- WUICore.lua
-- Minimal virtual UI + hooks + reconciler for WoW.
-- Core API: WUI.createElement, WUI.render, WUI.useState
-- Author: YourName

WUI = WUI or {}

-- internal
local hookState = {}
local currentInstance = nil
local currentHookIndex = 0

-- frame registry: map path -> { frame=..., vnode=... }
local registry = {}

-- vnode creator
local function vnode(type, props, ...)
    local children = {...}
    local ch = {}
    for i=1,#children do
        local c = children[i]
        if c ~= nil then
            local t = type(c)
            if t == "table" and c.type and c.props then
                table.insert(ch, c)
            elseif t == "string" or t == "number" then
                table.insert(ch, { type = "Text", props = { text = tostring(c) }, children = {} })
            end
        end
    end
    return { type = type, props = props or {}, children = ch }
end

function WUI.createElement(type, props, ...)
    return vnode(type, props, ...)
end

-- hooks
local function resetHooks(instanceId)
    currentInstance = instanceId
    currentHookIndex = 0
    hookState[instanceId] = hookState[instanceId] or { hooks = {}, rerender = nil }
end

function WUI.useState(initial)
    assert(currentInstance, "useState must be used during render")
    currentHookIndex = currentHookIndex + 1
    local bucket = hookState[currentInstance].hooks
    if bucket[currentHookIndex] == nil then bucket[currentHookIndex] = initial end
    local idx = currentHookIndex
    local function setter(v)
        bucket[idx] = v
        local r = hookState[currentInstance].rerender
        if r then r() end
    end
    return function() return bucket[idx] end, setter
end

-- helpers to build path
local function makePath(parent, key)
    if parent == "" then return tostring(key) end
    return parent .. "/" .. tostring(key)
end

-- create real frame from vnode (basic types)
local function createFrame(vnode, parentFrame, path)
    local t = vnode.type
    local p = vnode.props or {}
    local f = nil

    if t == "Frame" then
        f = CreateFrame("Frame", nil, parentFrame)
        f:SetSize(p.width or 200, p.height or 100)
        if p.point then
            f:SetPoint(unpack(p.point))
        else
            f:SetPoint("CENTER", parentFrame or UIParent, "CENTER", p.x or 0, p.y or 0)
        end
        if p.bg then
            local tex = f:CreateTexture(nil, "BACKGROUND")
            tex:SetAllPoints(f)
            tex:SetColorTexture(unpack(p.bg))
            f._bg = tex
        end
    elseif t == "Button" then
        local b = CreateFrame("Button", nil, parentFrame, "UIPanelButtonTemplate")
        b:SetSize(p.width or 120, p.height or 24)
        if p.point then b:SetPoint(unpack(p.point)) else b:SetPoint("CENTER", parentFrame or UIParent, "CENTER", p.x or 0, p.y or 0) end
        if p.text and b.SetText then b:SetText(p.text) end
        if p.onClick then b:SetScript("OnClick", p.onClick) end
        f = b
    elseif t == "Text" then
        local parent = parentFrame or UIParent
        local fs = parent:CreateFontString(nil, "OVERLAY", p.font or "GameFontNormal")
        if p.point then fs:SetPoint(unpack(p.point)) else fs:SetPoint("CENTER", parent, "CENTER", p.x or 0, p.y or 0) end
        fs:SetText(p.text or "")
        f = fs
    else
        -- custom component (table with type function handled upstream) or fallback frame
        f = CreateFrame("Frame", nil, parentFrame)
        f:SetSize(p.width or 100, p.height or 30)
    end

    registry[path] = registry[path] or {}
    registry[path].frame = f
    registry[path].vnode = vnode
    f:RegisterForClicks("AnyUp")
    return f
end

local function updateFrame(frame, vnode)
    if not frame or not vnode then return end
    local t = vnode.type
    local p = vnode.props or {}
    if t == "Frame" then
        if p.width or p.height then frame:SetSize(p.width or frame:GetWidth(), p.height or frame:GetHeight()) end
        if p.point then frame:ClearAllPoints(); frame:SetPoint(unpack(p.point)) end
        if p.bg then
            if not frame._bg then
                local tex = frame:CreateTexture(nil, "BACKGROUND"); tex:SetAllPoints(frame); frame._bg = tex
            end
            frame._bg:SetColorTexture(unpack(p.bg))
        end
    elseif t == "Button" then
        if p.text and frame.SetText then frame:SetText(p.text) end
        if p.onClick then frame:SetScript("OnClick", p.onClick) end
        if p.point then frame:ClearAllPoints(); frame:SetPoint(unpack(p.point)) end
    elseif t == "Text" then
        if frame.SetText and p.text then frame:SetText(p.text) end
        if p.point then frame:ClearAllPoints(); frame:SetPoint(unpack(p.point)) end
    end
end

local function destroyPath(path)
    local entry = registry[path]
    if not entry then return end
    local f = entry.frame
    if f and not f:IsForbidden() then
        f:Hide()
        f:SetParent(nil)
        if f.SetScript then f:SetScript("OnClick", nil) end
    end
    registry[path] = nil
end

local function reconcile(vnode, parentFrame, path)
    if not vnode then
        destroyPath(path)
        return
    end

    local existing = registry[path] and registry[path].vnode
    if (not existing) or (existing.type ~= vnode.type) then
        destroyPath(path)
        local frame = createFrame(vnode, parentFrame, path)
        -- children
        for i, child in ipairs(vnode.children or {}) do
            reconcile(child, frame, makePath(path, i))
        end
    else
        local frame = registry[path].frame
        updateFrame(frame, vnode)
        -- reconcile children by index
        local newCount = #vnode.children
        for i=1,newCount do
            reconcile(vnode.children[i], registry[path].frame, makePath(path, i))
        end
        -- remove leftovers
        local i = newCount + 1
        while true do
            local childPath = makePath(path, i)
            if registry[childPath] then
                destroyPath(childPath)
                i = i + 1
            else break end
        end
        registry[path].vnode = vnode
    end
end

-- render entrypoint: accepts component function or vnode; instanceId used for hooking
function WUI.render(rootComponentOrVNode, parentFrame, instanceId)
    instanceId = instanceId or "root"
    hookState[instanceId] = hookState[instanceId] or {}
    hookState[instanceId].rerender = function()
        WUI.render(rootComponentOrVNode, parentFrame, instanceId)
    end

    resetHooks(instanceId)

    local vtree
    if type(rootComponentOrVNode) == "function" then
        vtree = rootComponentOrVNode()
    else
        vtree = rootComponentOrVNode
    end

    reconcile(vtree, parentFrame or UIParent, "")
end

-- expose registry for debug
WUI._registry = registry
WUI._hookState = hookState

return WUI
```

```lua
-- Textures.lua
-- Simple texture manager: register assets, return texture path or create texture on frames.
-- This does not convert files; it assumes native files exist under assets/ (tga/blp).
-- Author: YourName

local Textures = {}

-- assets table: id -> { path = "Interface/AddOns/NextUI/assets/...", width = n, height = n, coords = {l,t,r,b} optional }
Textures.assets = Textures.assets or {}

-- Register assets via a Lua table (could be generated by build step)
function Textures.registerAssets(tbl)
    for k,v in pairs(tbl) do
        Textures.assets[k] = v
    end
end

-- Get asset metadata
function Textures.getAsset(id)
    return Textures.assets[id]
end

-- Ensure texture is applied to a frame; returns the created texture object
function Textures.applyTexture(frame, id, layer, subName)
    if not frame then return end
    local meta = Textures.getAsset(id)
    if not meta then
        -- fallback: treat id as raw path
        local t = frame:CreateTexture(subName, layer or "ARTWORK")
        t:SetTexture(id)
        return t
    end
    local t = frame:CreateTexture(subName, layer or "ARTWORK")
    t:SetTexture(meta.path)
    if meta.coords then
        t:SetTexCoord(unpack(meta.coords))
    end
    if meta.width and meta.height then
        t:SetSize(meta.width, meta.height)
    end
    return t
end

-- Simple helper to create an Image frame with asset id
function Textures.createImage(parent, id, props)
    props = props or {}
    local f = CreateFrame("Frame", nil, parent)
    local meta = Textures.getAsset(id)
    local tex = f:CreateTexture(nil, props.layer or "ARTWORK")
    if meta then
        tex:SetTexture(meta.path)
        if meta.coords then tex:SetTexCoord(unpack(meta.coords)) end
        local w = props.width or meta.width or 32
        local h = props.height or meta.height or 32
        f:SetSize(w,h)
        tex:SetAllPoints(f)
    else
        tex:SetTexture(id) -- path fallback
        f:SetSize(props.width or 32, props.height or 32)
        tex:SetAllPoints(f)
    end
    if props.point then f:SetPoint(unpack(props.point)) else f:SetPoint("CENTER", parent, "CENTER", props.x or 0, props.y or 0) end
    return f, tex
end

-- Example: pre-register local assets if present
-- Textures.registerAssets({
--   logo = { path = "Interface\\AddOns\\NextUI\\assets\\logo.tga", width = 128, height = 128 },
-- })

return Textures
```

```lua
-- Router.lua
-- Simple pages registry and client-side navigation. Pages register with Router.register("route", componentFn)
-- Router.navigate("route") mounts that page via WUI.render
-- Author: YourName

local Router = {}

Router.pages = Router.pages or {}
Router.current = nil
Router.parent = UIParent -- default root

-- Register a page (route string -> component function)
function Router.register(route, componentFn)
    Router.pages[route] = componentFn
end

-- navigate to route
function Router.navigate(route)
    local comp = Router.pages[route]
    if not comp then
        DEFAULT_CHAT_FRAME:AddMessage("Router: no page for route '" .. tostring(route) .. "'")
        return
    end
    Router.current = route
    -- mount page using WUI.render
    if WUI and WUI.render then
        WUI.render(function() return comp() end, Router.parent, "router_root")
    end
end

-- Link factory: returns a Button vnode that onClick navigates
function Router.Link(props)
    props = props or {}
    local route = props.to
    local text = props.text or props.children or "Link"
    local btnProps = {
        text = text,
        width = props.width or 120,
        height = props.height or 24,
        onClick = function() Router.navigate(route) end,
        point = props.point
    }
    return WUI.createElement("Button", btnProps)
end

-- Set parent for rendering (UIParent or custom frame)
function Router.setParent(frame)
    Router.parent = frame or UIParent
end

return Router
```

---

## `core/Components.lua`

(Convenience factories integrating Textures manager)

```lua
-- Components.lua
-- Basic components: Frame, Button, Text, Image that return vnodes for WUI
-- Author: YourName

local Textures = require and require("core.Textures") or Textures -- fallback if loader differs
-- In our addon layout, modules are loaded sequentially; assume Textures is global table

local C = {}

local function Frame(props, ...)
    return WUI.createElement("Frame", props, ...)
end

local function Button(props, ...)
    return WUI.createElement("Button", props, ...)
end

local function Text(props)
    return WUI.createElement("Text", props)
end

local function Image(props)
    props = props or {}
    -- Image returns a Frame vnode that will be created and inside createFrame we didn't implement image injection
    -- So we make a Frame with a hook: props._image = { id, width, height } ; reconciler will create frame then pages can call Textures.applyTexture after mount if needed.
    -- For simplicity, we'll store texture id in props and later code may apply via Textures.applyTexture when creating real frame.
    return WUI.createElement("Frame", { width = props.width or 32, height = props.height or 32, point = props.point, _texture = props.src }, -- children nil
    )
end

C.Frame = Frame
C.Button = Button
C.Text = Text
C.Image = Image

return C
```

**Note:** The minimal reconciler in `WUICore.lua` does not automatically map `_texture` props into real `CreateTexture` calls for Frame nodes. This is deliberate to keep the core tiny; in next iteration we’ll extend `createFrame` to look for `vnode.props._texture` and call `Textures.applyTexture` to create and attach the texture automatically. -- pages/index.lua

```lua
local Components = Components or _G.Components
local Textures = Textures or _G.Textures

-- simple page component
local function IndexPage()
    local getCount, setCount = WUI.useState(0)

    local function inc() setCount(getCount() + 1) end

    return Components.Frame({ width = 320, height = 160, point = { "CENTER", UIParent, "CENTER", 0, 0 }, bg = {0,0,0,0.5} },
        Components.Text({ text = "NextUI Demo", point = {"TOP", UIParent, "TOP", 0, -80} }),
        Components.Text({ text = "Count: " .. tostring(getCount()), point = {"TOP", UIParent, "TOP", 0, -100} }),

-- Register pages
```

Claude Code Router doesn't support direct GPT API key integration, as it’s designed for OpenAI-compatible endpoints like OpenRouter. Here's how to set it up with an OpenRouter API key to route requests to GPT models:

1. **Install Node.js**: Ensure Node.js (v18+) is installed.
2. **Install Claude Code**: Run `npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`.
3. **Install Claude Code Router**: Run `npm install -g @musistudio/claude-code-router`.
4. **Get OpenRouter API Key**: Sign up at openrouter.ai, navigate to the API Keys section, create a key, and copy it.
5. **Configure Router**: Create or edit `~/.claude-code-router/config.json` with:
   ```json
   {
     "Providers": [
       {
         "name": "openrouter",
         "api_base_url": "https://openrouter.ai/api/v1/chat/completions",
         "api_key": "your-openrouter-api-key",
         "models": ["openai/gpt-4", "openai/gpt-3.5-turbo"]
       }
     ],
     "Router": {
       "default": "openrouter,openai/gpt-4"
     }
   }
   ```
   Replace `your-openrouter-api-key` with your key.
6. **Start Router**: Run `ccr` to start Claude Code Router.
7. **Use Claude Code**: Run `claude` and use as normal; requests route through OpenRouter to GPT models.

**Note**: You need an OpenRouter account, as direct OpenAI GPT API keys aren't supported. For pricing, visit https://openrouter.ai.[](https://github.com/musistudio/claude-code-router)[](https://claudelog.com/addons/claude-code-router/)

---

## ✅ Understanding the Scope of the BLU Addon

### 🎮 What is BLU?

**BLU** is a **modular World of Warcraft addon** designed to **enhance game events** like achievements, leveling, quests, and reputations with **custom sound cues and UI overlays**. It is organized as a clean, self-contained addon with no external dependencies.

---

## 🧠 Core Design Principles

* **Modular architecture**: Each gameplay mechanic (e.g., achievements, quests) is a separate module.
* **Central core framework**: Handles event registration, config, and addon lifecycle.
* **Sound and media driven**: Custom `.ogg` files mapped to game events.
* **UI abstraction**: Panels and widgets are separated into template-driven interfaces.
* **Localization support**: Structured to support multiple languages.
* **Build tooling**: Includes scripts to batch-rename, consolidate, and manage sound files.

---

## 🗂️ Final Structure (Developer-Oriented Breakdown)

```plaintext
BLU/
│
├── 📦 Base Files

│   ├── README.md            # User-facing doc
│   ├── CLAUDE.md            # Developer/internal notes
│   ├── .gitignore, .pkgmeta # Git and CurseForge/Wago configs
│
├── 🧠 Core Framework (internal logic & engine)
│   └── core/
│       ├── init.lua             # Entry loader
│       ├── core.lua             # AddOn engine
│       ├── registry.lua         # Sound event mapping and registry
│       ├── loader.lua           # Module/component loader
│       ├── database.lua         # Persistent saved variables
│       ├── config.lua           # User config defaults
│       ├── commands.lua         # Slash commands
│       ├── sharedmedia.lua      # Interface with LibSharedMedia if needed
│       └── utils.lua            # Utility functions
│
├── 🔌 Feature Modules (modular event logic)
│   └── modules/
│       ├── Achievement/         # Achievement unlock handler
│       ├── BattlePet/           # Pet battle event logic
│       ├── Delve/               # Delve-specific logic (Dragonflight?)
│       ├── Honor/               # PvP honor tracking
│       ├── LevelUp/             # Leveling progress alerts
│       ├── Quest/               # Quest events + custom panel
│       ├── Renown/              # Renown rank-up support
│       ├── Reputation/          # Reputation gain/loss handlers
│       └── TradingPost/         # Trading Post notifications
│
├── 🖥️ UI Interface (panels, widgets, tabs)
│   └── interface/
│       ├── Design.lua           # Theme and layout settings
│       ├── Settings.lua         # Settings UI
│       ├── Tabs.lua             # Navigation tabs
│       ├── Widgets.lua          # Shared UI widgets

│       │   ├── About.lua

│
├── 🌍 Localization

│

│       │   ├── *.ogg            # 50+ game-themed alerts
│       └── Textures/            # UI assets (e.g., play button, preview)
│
├── 🔊 Sound Definitions
│   └── sound/
│       └── packs/
│           ├── finalfantasy.lua # Custom sound pack
│           └── packs.xml        # Master pack loader/index
│
├── 🧰 Tooling & Build Scripts
│   ├── consolidate_sounds.bat   # Merges or removes variants
│   ├── rename_sounds.ps1        # Normalizes sound filenames
│   └── .claude/                 # Local dev settings (Claude integration?)
│       └── settings.local.json
│
└── 🧹 Known Cleanup Artifacts (to fix/remove)
    ├── nul                             # OS bug file (remove manually)
    └── CUsersJosephGettingsBLUexclude.txt # Broken filename (rename/fix)
```

---

## 🧭 Recommended Organization Tips (Already Mostly Implemented)

* ✅ **One folder = one responsibility**: Already done with `/core`, `/modules`, `/interface`, `/media`, etc.
* ✅ **No mixed case filenames**: Except `.toc` and `.xml` (by Blizzard design)
* ✅ **All modules fully self-contained** (no cross-import chaos)
* ✅ **Future-proof**: `libs/` is ready, `Templates/` is staged for expansion

* ⚠️ **Optional**: Split `media/sounds` into subfolders (e.g. `media/sounds/levelup/`, `media/sounds/pvp/`) if it grows again

## ✅ BLU Addon is Now:

* **Modular**: Easily test and disable components
* **Media-rich**: Immediate game feedback through custom sounds
* **Clean**: Fast iteration, no tech debt
* **Dev-ready**: Auto-sync to WoW for local testing

1.content:
Of course. Here is a proposal for a new, logically organized repository structure for your addon. This structure separates concerns, making the project easier to navigate, maintain, and scale.

This organization is based on common best practices for software, particularly for game addons.

-----

### **Proposed Repository Structure**

The goal is to keep the root directory clean and group related files into logical folders.

```
YourAddonName/
│
├── 📁 Core/
│   ├── Core.lua               # Main addon logic, event handling, and initialization.
│   ├── Config.lua             # Default settings and configuration values.
│   └── API.lua                # Functions exposed for other addons to use.
│
├── 📁 Modules/
│   ├── 📁 Quest/
│   │   ├── Quest.lua          # Logic for the Quest module.
│   │   └── QuestOptions.lua   # Code for the Quest settings panel.
│   ├── 📁 AnotherModule/
│   │   ├── AnotherModule.lua
│   │   └── AnotherModuleOptions.lua
│   └── ...                    # (add a folder for each new module)
│
├── 📁 Interface/
│   ├── 📁 Templates/
│   │   └── SharedTemplates.xml # Reusable XML UI components (buttons, sliders).
│   ├── Settings.xml           # Main settings panel XML layout.
│   └── Settings.lua           # Code-behind for the main settings panel.
│
├── 📁 Media/
│   ├── 📁 Sounds/
│   │   ├── QuestAccept.ogg
│   │   └── QuestTurnIn.ogg
│   ├── 📁 Textures/
│   │   └── Logo.tga
│   └── 📁 Fonts/
│       └── CustomFont.ttf
│
├── 📁 Localization/
│   ├── enUS.lua               # English localization strings.
│   └── esMX.lua               # Spanish localization strings.
│
├── 📁 Libs/
│   └── LibSharedMedia-3.0/    # Folder for third-party libraries.
│
├── YourAddonName.toc          # The addon's Table of Contents file (essential).
├── README.md                  # Project description and instructions.
├── LICENSE                    # Your software license.
└── .gitignore                 # Files and folders for Git to ignore.

```

-----

### **Explanation of a Logical File Structure**

Here's why this structure makes sense:

  * **Root Directory**: The top level is kept minimal. It only contains essential project-wide files like the **`.toc`**, **`README`**, and **`LICENSE`**. This provides a clean entry point to the project.

  * **`Core/`**: This is the heart of your addon. It contains the central logic that isn't specific to any single feature. **`Config.lua`** holds all default variables, making them easy to find and change.

  * **`Modules/`**: This is the key to organization and scalability. Each distinct feature of your addon (like "Quest" tracking) gets its own folder. This makes your code **modular**. You can easily enable, disable, or work on a feature without affecting the others. Adding a new feature is as simple as creating a new folder here. 🛠️

  * **`Interface/`**: All files related to the User Interface (UI) are grouped here. This separates the visual presentation **(XML)** from the underlying logic **(Lua)**, which is a powerful design pattern.

  * **`Media/`**: All non-code assets live here, sorted by type. This keeps your sounds, textures, and fonts separate from the functional code, making them easy to manage and update. 🎵

  * **`Localization/`**: Placing all language files in one folder is crucial for maintainability. When you need to add a new language or update a translation string, you know exactly where to go. 🌎

  * **`Libs/`**: Third-party code should always be isolated in its own directory. This prevents it from getting mixed up with your original code and makes updating these libraries much simpler.

# 🎯 SQP | Simple Quest Plates! ![SQP Logo](https://github.com/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates/blob/main/images/logo.png?raw=true) ## 🎮 RGX Mods - RealmGX Community Project ### 🎯 _See quest progress at a glance on enemy nameplates!_ 🎯 **SQP | Simple Quest Plates!** is a professional World of Warcraft addon that displays quest progress icons directly on enemy nameplates. Know at a glance which enemies you need to defeat for your quests, how many items they drop, and your overall progress - all without cluttering your interface. As part of the **RGX Mods** collection, it delivers premium quality with extensive customization options, multi-language support, and seamless integration. *** ## 🌟 Join the RGX Mods Community! **💬 RealmGX Discord - Your Gaming Home!** [![Join Discord](https://img.shields.io/badge/Join Our Discord-RealmGX Community-7289da?style=for-the-badge&logo=discord&logoColor=white&labelColor=5865F2)](https://discord.gg/N7kdKAHVVF) **🎮 Realm Gamers eXtreme - Where WoW Enthusiasts Unite!** **✨ What awaits you in our Discord:** * 🛠️ Instant addon support from the RGX Mods team * 🎯 Feature requests and direct dev communication * 🚀 Beta testing opportunities for new releases * 🤝 Community of **WoW players** sharing tips and experiences * 📢 First to know about new RGX Mods releases * 🎉 Events, giveaways, and community activities *** ## 🎯 What is SQP? **SQP | Simple Quest Plates!** enhances your World of Warcraft experience by displaying quest progress icons directly on enemy nameplates. Know at a glance which enemies you need to defeat for your quests, how many items they drop, and your overall progress - all without cluttering your interface. ![SQP Options Panel](https://github.com/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates/blob/main/images/in-game-options.png?raw=true) *** ## ✨ Features 🎯 Quest Icons - Display quest progress directly on enemy nameplates 🎨 Fully Customizable - Adjust colors, fonts, sizes, and positions 📊 Item Priority - Shows item counts before kill counts when both are needed 🌍 Multi-Language - Supports English, German, Spanish, French, and Russian ⚡ Lightweight - Minimal performance impact with efficient caching 🛡️ Combat Options - Hide icons during combat or in instances 🎨 Live Preview - See changes in real-time in the options panel 🎯 Smart Detection - Automatically tracks all active quests in your area 🔧 Position Control - Place icons on left or right side with X/Y offsets 🎨 Font Customization - Size, outline style, and shadow effects 🌈 Color Options - Different colors for kill, item, and progress quests 🖼️ Icon Tinting - Optional icon color tinting 💾 Account-Wide - Settings saved across all characters 🛡️ Error-Free - Comprehensive error handling 📝 Slash Commands - Quick access to all features *** ## 🚀 Quick Start 1. **Install** SQP from your preferred platform 2. **Launch** World of Warcraft 3. **Type** `/sqp` to open the options panel 4. **Customize** your quest display preferences 5. **Quest** with enhanced awareness! *** ## 📋 Command Reference
/sqp # Open the options panel
/sqp help # Display all available commands
/sqp test # Test quest detection on current nameplates
/sqp on # Enable the addon
/sqp off # Disable the addon
/sqp status # Show current settings
/sqp scale <0.5-2.0> # Set icon scale
/sqp offset <x> <y> # Set icon position offset
/sqp anchor <left/right> # Set which side of nameplate to anchor to
/sqp reset # Reset all settings to defaults
*** ## 🎨 Customization Options ### 📐 Position & Scale * **Icon Scale:** 0.5x to 2.0x size adjustment * **X/Y Offset:** -50 to +50 pixel positioning * **Anchor Side:** Left or right side attachment ### 🎨 Font Settings * **Font Size:** 8 to 20 point sizes * **Outline Style:** Thin, Normal, or Thick * **Shadow Color:** Colored shadow effects for depth * _Note:_ WoW outlines are always black, but shadows add color ### 🌈 Color Customization * **Kill Quests:** Default golden yellow * **Item Quests:** Default green * **Progress Quests:** Default cyan * **Icon Tinting:** Optional color overlay ### ⚙️ Behavior Options * **Hide in Combat:** Keep your combat view clean * **Hide in Instances:** Disable in dungeons/raids * **Debug Mode:** Troubleshooting assistance * **Chat Messages:** Toggle addon notifications *** ## 🎮 How It Works ### Quest Detection SQP uses Blizzard's quest API to detect which enemies are related to your active quests: * Automatically scans all nameplates in view * Updates in real-time as you accept/complete quests * Prioritizes item drops over kill counts for dual-objective quests ### Performance * Efficient caching system for quest data * Minimal CPU usage with smart update cycles * No impact on frame rates *** ## 📥 Installation 1. **Download** from your preferred platform: * [CurseForge](https://www.curseforge.com/wow/addons/simple-quest-plates) * [Wago.io](https://addons.wago.io/addons/simple-quest-plates) * [WoWInterface](https://www.wowinterface.com/downloads/info26795-SimpleQuestPlates.html) * [GitHub](https://github.com/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates) 2. **Extract** to your WoW AddOns directory: * World of Warcraft/retail/Interface/AddOns 3. **Restart** WoW and configure with `/sqp` *** ## 🌍 Localization SQP supports multiple languages: * **English** (enUS) * **Deutsch** (deDE) * **Español** (esES) * **Français** (frFR) * **Русский** (ruRU) _Want to help translate? Join our Discord!_ *** ## 🛠️ Configuration Tips ### Recommended Settings: * **Combat Players:** Enable "Hide in Combat" for cleaner fights * **Dungeon/Raid:** Enable "Hide in Instances" to reduce clutter * **Questing Focus:** Larger scale (1.5x) and bright colors * **Minimalist:** Smaller scale (0.8x) with subtle positioning ### Troubleshooting: * Use `/sqp test` to verify quest detection * Enable Debug Mode for detailed logging * Join our Discord for instant support *** ## 🐛 Bug Reports Found a bug? Report it: * [GitHub Issues](https://github.com/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates/issues) * Join our Discord for instant support *** ## 💻 Development Activity ### 📊 WakaTime Development Stats [![wakatime](https://wakatime.com/badge/user/a0b54ba5-f8b2-4aba-82f9-a1e1ad1a1e6e.svg?style=for-the-badge)](https://wakatime.com/@donniedice) ### 📈 Weekly Coding Activity [![DonnieDice's WakaTime stats](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api/wakatime?username=donniedice&theme=tokyonight&hide_border=true&layout=compact&langs_count=10)](https://wakatime.com/@donniedice) ### ⏱️ Time Tracking [![](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api/wakatime?username=donniedice&theme=tokyonight&hide_border=true&layout=default&range=last_7_days&custom_title=Last 7 Days Coding Activity)](https://wakatime.com/@donniedice) ### 💻 Languages Used This Week [![Top Langs](https://github-readme-stats.vercel.app/api/top-langs/?username=donniedice&layout=compact&theme=tokyonight&hide_border=true)](https://github.com/donniedice) ### 🔥 Streak Stats [![GitHub Streak](https://github-readme-streak-stats.herokuapp.com/?user=donniedice&theme=tokyonight&hide_border=true)](https://github.com/donniedice) *** ## 📊 Repository Statistics [![GitHub Activity Graph](https://github-readme-activity-graph.vercel.app/graph?username=donniedice&theme=react-dark&hide_border=true)](https://github.com/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates) *** ## 📈 Project Metrics Total Lines of Code: ![Lines of code](https://img.shields.io/tokei/lines/github/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates?style=flat-square) Repository Size: ![GitHub repo size](https://img.shields.io/github/repo-size/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates?style=flat-square) Last Commit: ![GitHub last commit](https://img.shields.io/github/last-commit/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates?style=flat-square) Open Issues: ![GitHub issues](https://img.shields.io/github/issues/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates?style=flat-square) Languages: ![GitHub top language](https://img.shields.io/github/languages/top/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates?style=flat-square) File Structure: Modular design with 20+ specialized files Supported Languages: 5 localizations Options Panel: 5 organized tabs Customization Options: 15+ settings *** ## name: Package and Release

  on:
    push:
      tags:
        - 'v*'  # Triggers only on version tags like v1.0.0,
  v1.0.0-alpha, etc.

  env:
    CF_API_KEY: ${{ secrets.CF_API_KEY }}
    WOWI_API_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.WOWI_API_TOKEN }}
    WAGO_API_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.WAGO_API_TOKEN }}
    GITHUB_OAUTH: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}

  jobs:
    release:
      runs-on: ubuntu-latest
      steps:
        - name: Clone Project
          uses: actions/checkout@v4
          with:
            fetch-depth: 0

        - name: Configure Git user
          run: |
            git config --global user.name "donniedice"
            git config --global user.email
  "donniedice@protonmail.com"

        - name: Set Release Type
          id: set_release_type
          run: |
            TAG_NAME=${{ github.ref }}
            if [[ "$TAG_NAME" == *"beta"* ]]; then
              echo "::set-output name=release_type::beta"
            elif [[ "$TAG_NAME" == *"alpha"* ]]; then
              echo "::set-output name=release_type::alpha"
            else
              echo "::set-output name=release_type::release"
            fi

        - name: Extract Version from TOC
          id: extract_version
          run: |
            version=$(grep -oP '^## Version: \K(.*)' ./*.toc)
            echo "::set-output name=version::$version"

        - name: Package and Release
          uses: BigWigsMods/packager@master
          with:
            release-type: ${{
  steps.set_release_type.outputs.release_type }}

# 🎯 SQP | Simple Quest Plates! ![SQP Logo](https://github.com/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates/blob/main/images/logo.png?raw=true) ## 🎮 RGX Mods - RealmGX Community Project ### 🎯 _See quest progress at a glance on enemy nameplates!_ 🎯 **SQP | Simple Quest Plates!** is a professional World of Warcraft addon that displays quest progress icons directly on enemy nameplates. Know at a glance which enemies you need to defeat for your quests, how many items they drop, and your overall progress - all without cluttering your interface. As part of the **RGX Mods** collection, it delivers premium quality with extensive customization options, multi-language support, and seamless integration. *** ## 🌟 Join the RGX Mods Community! **💬 RealmGX Discord - Your Gaming Home!** [![Join Discord](https://img.shields.io/badge/Join%20Our%20Discord-RealmGX%20Community-7289da?style=for-the-badge&logo=discord&logoColor=white&labelColor=5865F2)](https://discord.gg/N7kdKAHVVF) **🎮 Realm Gamers eXtreme - Where WoW Enthusiasts Unite!** **✨ What awaits you in our Discord:** * 🛠️ Instant addon support from the RGX Mods team * 🎯 Feature requests and direct dev communication * 🚀 Beta testing opportunities for new releases * 🤝 Community of **WoW players** sharing tips and experiences * 📢 First to know about new RGX Mods releases * 🎉 Events, giveaways, and community activities *** ## 🎯 What is SQP? **SQP | Simple Quest Plates!** enhances your World of Warcraft experience by displaying quest progress icons directly on enemy nameplates. Know at a glance which enemies you need to defeat for your quests, how many items they drop, and your overall progress - all without cluttering your interface. ![SQP Options Panel](https://github.com/donniedice/SimpleQuestPlates/blob/main/images/in-game-options.png?raw=true) *** ## ✨ Features 🎯 Quest Icons - Display quest progress directly on enemy nameplates 🎨 Fully Customizable - Adjust colors, fonts, sizes, and positions 📊 Item Priority - Shows item counts before kill counts when both are needed 🌍 Multi-Language - Supports English, German, Spanish, French, and Russian ⚡ Lightweight - Minimal performance impact with efficient caching 🛡️ Combat Options - Hide icons during combat or in instances 🎨 Live Preview - See changes in real-time in the options panel 🎯 Smart Detection - Automatically tracks all active quests in your area 🔧 Position Control - Place icons on left or right side with X/Y offsets 🎨 Font Customization - Size, outline style, and shadow effects 🌈 Color Options - Different colors for kill, item, and progress quests 🖼️ Icon Tinting - Optional icon color tinting 💾 Account-Wide - Settings saved across all characters 🛡️ Error-Free - Comprehensive error handling 📝 Slash Commands - Quick access to all features *** ## 🚀 Quick Start 1. **Install** SQP from your preferred platform 2. **Launch** World of Warcraft 3. **Type** `/sqp` to open the options panel 4. **Customize** your quest display preferences 5. **Quest** with enhanced awareness! *** ## 📋 Command Reference
/sqp # Open the options panel
/sqp help # Display all available commands
/sqp test # Test quest detection on current nameplates
/sqp on # Enable the addon

# Changelog

## 1.0.73

- MCP: Support multiple config files with `--mcp-config file1.json file2.json`
- MCP: Press Esc to cancel OAuth authentication flows
- Bash: Improved command validation and reduced false security warnings
- UI: Enhanced spinner animations and status line visual hierarchy
- Linux: Added support for Alpine and musl-based distributions (requires separate ripgrep installation)

## 1.0.72

- Ask permissions: have Claude Code always ask for confirmation to use specific tools with /permissions

## 1.0.71

- Background commands: (Ctrl-b) to run any Bash command in the background so Claude can keep working (great for dev servers, tailing logs, etc.)
- Customizable status line: add your terminal prompt to Claude Code with /statusline

## 1.0.70

- Performance: Optimized message rendering for better performance with large contexts
- Windows: Fixed native file search, ripgrep, and subagent functionality
- Added support for @-mentions in slash command arguments

## 1.0.69

- Upgraded Opus to version 4.1

## 1.0.68

- Fix incorrect model names being used for certain commands like `/pr-comments`
- Windows: improve permissions checks for allow / deny tools and project trust. This may create a new project entry in `.claude.json` - manually merge the history field if desired.
- Windows: improve sub-process spawning to eliminate "No such file or directory" when running commands like pnpm
- Enhanced /doctor command with CLAUDE.md and MCP tool context for self-serve debugging
- SDK: Added canUseTool callback support for tool confirmation
- Added `disableAllHooks` setting
- Improved file suggestions performance in large repos

## 1.0.65

- IDE: Fixed connection stability issues and error handling for diagnostics
- Windows: Fixed shell environment setup for users without .bashrc files

## 1.0.64

- Agents: Added model customization support - you can now specify which model an agent should use
- Agents: Fixed unintended access to the recursive agent tool
- Hooks: Added systemMessage field to hook JSON output for displaying warnings and context
- SDK: Fixed user input tracking across multi-turn conversations
- Added hidden files to file search and @-mention suggestions

## 1.0.63

- Windows: Fixed file search, @agent mentions, and custom slash commands functionality

## 1.0.62

- Added @-mention support with typeahead for custom agents. @<your-custom-agent> to invoke it
- Hooks: Added SessionStart hook for new session initialization
- /add-dir command now supports typeahead for directory paths
- Improved network connectivity check reliability

## 1.0.61

- Transcript mode (Ctrl+R): Changed Esc to exit transcript mode rather than interrupt
- Settings: Added `--settings` flag to load settings from a JSON file
- Settings: Fixed resolution of settings files paths that are symlinks
- OTEL: Fixed reporting of wrong organization after authentication changes
- Slash commands: Fixed permissions checking for allowed-tools with Bash
- IDE: Added support for pasting images in VSCode MacOS using ⌘+V
- IDE: Added `CLAUDE_CODE_AUTO_CONNECT_IDE=false` for disabling IDE auto-connection
- Added `CLAUDE_CODE_SHELL_PREFIX` for wrapping Claude and user-provided shell commands run by Claude Code

## 1.0.60

- You can now create custom subagents for specialized tasks! Run /agents to get started

## 1.0.59

- SDK: Added tool confirmation support with canUseTool callback
- SDK: Allow specifying env for spawned process
- Hooks: Exposed PermissionDecision to hooks (including "ask")
- Hooks: UserPromptSubmit now supports additionalContext in advanced JSON output
- Fixed issue where some Max users that specified Opus would still see fallback to Sonnet

## 1.0.58

- Added support for reading PDFs
- MCP: Improved server health status display in 'claude mcp list'
- Hooks: Added CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR env var for hook commands

## 1.0.57

- Added support for specifying a model in slash commands
- Improved permission messages to help Claude understand allowed tools
- Fix: Remove trailing newlines from bash output in terminal wrapping

## 1.0.56

- Windows: Enabled shift+tab for mode switching on versions of Node.js that support terminal VT mode
- Fixes for WSL IDE detection
- Fix an issue causing awsRefreshHelper changes to .aws directory not to be picked up

## 1.0.55

- Clarified knowledge cutoff for Opus 4 and Sonnet 4 models
- Windows: fixed Ctrl+Z crash
- SDK: Added ability to capture error logging
- Add --system-prompt-file option to override system prompt in print mode

## 1.0.54

- Hooks: Added UserPromptSubmit hook and the current working directory to hook inputs
- Custom slash commands: Added argument-hint to frontmatter
- Windows: OAuth uses port 45454 and properly constructs browser URL
- Windows: mode switching now uses alt + m, and plan mode renders properly
- Shell: Switch to in-memory shell snapshot to fix file-related errors

## 1.0.53

- Updated @-mention file truncation from 100 lines to 2000 lines
- Add helper script settings for AWS token refresh: awsAuthRefresh (for foreground operations like aws sso login) and awsCredentialExport (for background operation with STS-like response).

## 1.0.52

- Added support for MCP server instructions

## 1.0.51

- Added support for native Windows (requires Git for Windows)
- Added support for Bedrock API keys through environment variable AWS_BEARER_TOKEN_BEDROCK
- Settings: /doctor can now help you identify and fix invalid setting files
- `--append-system-prompt` can now be used in interactive mode, not just --print/-p.
- Increased auto-compact warning threshold from 60% to 80%
- Fixed an issue with handling user directories with spaces for shell snapshots
- OTEL resource now includes os.type, os.version, host.arch, and wsl.version (if running on Windows Subsystem for Linux)
- Custom slash commands: Fixed user-level commands in subdirectories
- Plan mode: Fixed issue where rejected plan from sub-task would get discarded

## 1.0.48

- Fixed a bug in v1.0.45 where the app would sometimes freeze on launch
- Added progress messages to Bash tool based on the last 5 lines of command output
- Added expanding variables support for MCP server configuration
- Moved shell snapshots from /tmp to ~/.claude for more reliable Bash tool calls
- Improved IDE extension path handling when Claude Code runs in WSL
- Hooks: Added a PreCompact hook
- Vim mode: Added c, f/F, t/T

## 1.0.45

- Redesigned Search (Grep) tool with new tool input parameters and features
- Disabled IDE diffs for notebook files, fixing "Timeout waiting after 1000ms" error
- Fixed config file corruption issue by enforcing atomic writes
- Updated prompt input undo to Ctrl+\_ to avoid breaking existing Ctrl+U behavior, matching zsh's undo shortcut
- Stop Hooks: Fixed transcript path after /clear and fixed triggering when loop ends with tool call
- Custom slash commands: Restored namespacing in command names based on subdirectories. For example, .claude/commands/frontend/component.md is now /frontend:component, not /component.

## 1.0.44

- New /export command lets you quickly export a conversation for sharing
- MCP: resource_link tool results are now supported
- MCP: tool annotations and tool titles now display in /mcp view
- Changed Ctrl+Z to suspend Claude Code. Resume by running `fg`. Prompt input undo is now Ctrl+U.

## 1.0.43

- Fixed a bug where the theme selector was saving excessively
- Hooks: Added EPIPE system error handling

## 1.0.42

- Added tilde (`~`) expansion support to `/add-dir` command

## 1.0.41

- Hooks: Split Stop hook triggering into Stop and SubagentStop
- Hooks: Enabled optional timeout configuration for each command
- Hooks: Added "hook_event_name" to hook input
- Fixed a bug where MCP tools would display twice in tool list
- New tool parameters JSON for Bash tool in `tool_decision` event

## 1.0.40

- Fixed a bug causing API connection errors with UNABLE_TO_GET_ISSUER_CERT_LOCALLY if `NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS` was set

## 1.0.39

- New Active Time metric in OpenTelemetry logging

## 1.0.38

- Released hooks. Special thanks to community input in https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/issues/712. Docs: https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/hooks

## 1.0.37

- Remove ability to set `Proxy-Authorization` header via ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN or apiKeyHelper

## 1.0.36

- Web search now takes today's date into context
- Fixed a bug where stdio MCP servers were not terminating properly on exit

## 1.0.35

- Added support for MCP OAuth Authorization Server discovery

## 1.0.34

- Fixed a memory leak causing a MaxListenersExceededWarning message to appear

## 1.0.33

- Improved logging functionality with session ID support
- Added prompt input undo functionality (Ctrl+Z and vim 'u' command)
- Improvements to plan mode

## 1.0.32

- Updated loopback config for litellm
- Added forceLoginMethod setting to bypass login selection screen

## 1.0.31

- Fixed a bug where ~/.claude.json would get reset when file contained invalid JSON

## 1.0.30

- Custom slash commands: Run bash output, @-mention files, enable thinking with thinking keywords
- Improved file path autocomplete with filename matching
- Added timestamps in Ctrl-r mode and fixed Ctrl-c handling
- Enhanced jq regex support for complex filters with pipes and select

## 1.0.29

- Improved CJK character support in cursor navigation and rendering

## 1.0.28

- Slash commands: Fix selector display during history navigation
- Resizes images before upload to prevent API size limit errors
- Added XDG_CONFIG_HOME support to configuration directory
- Performance optimizations for memory usage
- New attributes (terminal.type, language) in OpenTelemetry logging

## 1.0.27

- Streamable HTTP MCP servers are now supported
- Remote MCP servers (SSE and HTTP) now support OAuth
- MCP resources can now be @-mentioned
- /resume slash command to switch conversations within Claude Code

## 1.0.25

- Slash commands: moved "project" and "user" prefixes to descriptions
- Slash commands: improved reliability for command discovery
- Improved support for Ghostty
- Improved web search reliability

## 1.0.24

- Improved /mcp output
- Fixed a bug where settings arrays got overwritten instead of merged

## 1.0.23

- Released TypeScript SDK: import @anthropic-ai/claude-code to get started
- Released Python SDK: pip install claude-code-sdk to get started

## 1.0.22

- SDK: Renamed `total_cost` to `total_cost_usd`

## 1.0.21

- Improved editing of files with tab-based indentation
- Fix for tool_use without matching tool_result errors
- Fixed a bug where stdio MCP server processes would linger after quitting Claude Code

## 1.0.18

- Added --add-dir CLI argument for specifying additional working directories
- Added streaming input support without require -p flag
- Improved startup performance and session storage performance
- Added CLAUDE_BASH_MAINTAIN_PROJECT_WORKING_DIR environment variable to freeze working directory for bash commands

## 1.0.17

- We now emit messages from sub-tasks in -p mode (look for the parent_tool_use_id property)
- Fixed crashes when the VS Code diff tool is invoked multiple times quickly

- Update Claude Code process title to display "claude" instead of "node"

## 1.0.11

- Claude Code can now also be used with a Claude Pro subscription
- Added /upgrade for smoother switching to Claude Max plans
- Improved UI for authentication from API keys and Bedrock/Vertex/external auth tokens
- Improved shell configuration error handling
- Improved todo list handling during compaction

## 1.0.10

- Added markdown table support
- Improved streaming performance

## 1.0.8

- Fixed Vertex AI region fallback when using CLOUD_ML_REGION
- Increased default otel interval from 1s -> 5s

- Fixed a regression where search tools unnecessarily asked for permissions

## 1.0.6

- Improved edit reliability for tab-indented files
- Respect CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR everywhere
- Reduced unnecessary tool permission prompts

## 1.0.4

- Fixed a bug where MCP tool errors weren't being parsed correctly

## 1.0.1

- Added `DISABLE_INTERLEAVED_THINKING` to give users the option to opt out of interleaved thinking.
- Improved model references to show provider-specific names (Sonnet 3.7 for Bedrock, Sonnet 4 for Console)
- Updated documentation links and OAuth process descriptions

## 1.0.0

- Claude Code is now generally available
- Introducing Sonnet 4 and Opus 4 models

- Fixed a regression in /cost reporting
- Deprecated MCP wizard interface in favor of other MCP commands
- Lots of other bugfixes and improvements

- CLAUDE.md files can now import other files. Add @path/to/file.md to ./CLAUDE.md to load additional files on launch

- MCP SSE server configs can now specify custom headers

- Fixed an issue where auto-compact was running twice

- Claude Code can now also be used with a Claude Max subscription (https://claude.ai/upgrade)

## 0.2.75

- Updated spinner to indicate tokens loaded and tool usage

- Print mode (-p) now supports streaming output via --output-format=stream-json

## 0.2.61

- Navigate menus with vim-style keys (j/k) or bash/emacs shortcuts (Ctrl+n/p) for faster interaction
- Enhanced image detection for more reliable clipboard paste functionality

## 0.2.59

- Copy+paste images directly into your prompt

- Quickly add to Memory by starting your message with '#'

## 0.2.53

- New web fetch tool lets Claude view URLs that you paste in

- Added ANSI color theme for better terminal compatibility
- Fixed issue where slash command arguments weren't being sent properly
